d": "f00af389-a5c3-9a2b-bdce-619a5a67fef8"}, "input": {"input": ["神经症:神经症，也被称为Neurosis，是一组以焦虑、抑郁、恐惧、强迫、疑病症状或神经衰弱症状为突出表现的精神障碍。这类疾病属于功能性精神疾病，被认为是心理生理障碍的一部分，通常没有可以证实的客观器质性病变。患者常感到多种躯体或精神上的不适，这些症状与患者的现实处境不相称，但患者对存在的症状感到痛苦和无能为力。尽管症状严重，患者通常无持久的精神病性症状，自知力完整或基本完整，且求治心切。\n\n神经症的病因学解释涉及巴甫洛夫条件反射研究和行为治疗，表明其发生与心理社会（环境）因素密切相关。患者病前多有一定的易患素质和个性特征，特别是强不均衡型性格者更易患病。疾病的发生与发展常受心理社会因素的影响，病程多迁延，进入中年后症状常可缓解或部分缓解。\n\n神经症在全球范围内具有较高的患病率，患者可能因感到痛苦、焦虑而无法摆脱，进而产生自杀行为。尽管神经症被归类为较轻的精神疾病，但其对患者的生活质量和心理健康的影响不容忽视。", "癔症:癔症，又称歇斯底里症，是一种与性格特征相关的精神疾病，尤其常见于具有艺术型或表演型人格特征的人群。该病症属于神经症的一种亚型，患者常表现出戏剧性的行为和情感反应，但这些症状并无相应的器质性病变基础。癔症的一个典型特征是，外部刺激可能引发患者产生热感等异常感觉。此外，癔症的痉挛发作可能表现为类似抽动样的动作，但这些症状通常具有原发精神障碍的特征，而非单纯的生理性反应。总体而言，癔症是一种复杂的精神心理疾病，其症状多样且与患者的性格特征密切相关。", "ICD-10:ICD-10, the 10th edition of the International Classification of Diseases, is a globally recognized diagnostic system used for classifying diseases, health conditions, and mental disorders. It serves as a standard tool for diagnosis and treatment across various medical fields and is widely adopted internationally. ICD-10 has made significant updates to its terminology and classifications, such as removing the term \"hysteria\" due to its ambiguous meaning and retaining the term \"neurasthenia\" while limiting its use. Additionally, it has reclassified certain conditions, such as Ganser syndrome, which is categorized under \"other dissociative (conversion) disorders,\" and acute and transient psychotic disorders and severe stress reactions, which are placed under specific categories. The system also uses the term \"harmful use\" synonymously with substance abuse and categorizes mental disorders due to physical diseases under section F06. Furthermore, ICD-10 has abandoned the overarching term \"neurosis\" but has retained several subtypes related to the concept by renaming or reclassifying them, ensuring their continued presence in the classification system. This comprehensive and evolving framework is utilized by researchers and clinicians, such as Fink and 孟凡强 et al., for diagnosing conditions like somatoform disorders, making it an essential tool in global healthcare.", "DSM-Ⅳ:The DSM-IV, or the fourth edition of the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, is a widely used diagnostic manual in psychiatry, particularly in the United States. It serves as a comprehensive guide for diagnosing mental disorders and includes a specific category for substance abuse. Notably, the DSM-IV removed the term \"hysteria,\" aligning with similar changes in the ICD-10. Additionally, while the DSM-IV abandoned the broader term \"neurosis,\" it retained several subtypes historically associated with the concept of neurosis by renaming or reclassifying them within the diagnostic framework. This approach ensured that these conditions remained part of the classification system, albeit under different terminology or categories. Overall, the DSM-IV represents a significant evolution in the field of psychiatric diagnosis, reflecting both continuity and adaptation in its approach to mental health disorders.", "CCMD-3:The **Chinese Classification of Mental Disorders, 3rd Edition (CCMD-3)** is a comprehensive diagnostic standard and classification system used in China for identifying, categorizing, and diagnosing a wide range of mental health disorders. Adopted by the Chinese Society of Psychiatry in 2001 and implemented nationwide, CCMD-3 serves as a critical tool for mental health professionals in China. It provides detailed criteria for diagnosing various conditions, including anxiety disorders (such as generalized anxiety disorder and panic disorder), obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) in both children and adults, post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), and specific phobias. Additionally, CCMD-3 addresses neurotic disorders, such as neurotic bulimia, neurasthenia (characterized by brain and body function weakness, emotional symptoms, and physical fatigue), and hysteria, which has been moved out of the neurosis category in this edition.\n\nThe system also covers stress-related disorders, including acute stress disorder, and categorizes stress-related conditions under the broader umbrella of hysteria, stress, and neurosis. CCMD-3 includes diagnostic criteria for eating disorders like anorexia nervosa and binge eating disorder, as well as sleep disorders such as insomnia, hypersomnia, and sleep-wake rhythm disorders. It further classifies somatic symptom disorders, somatoform disorders, and tic disorders, including Tourette Syndrome.\n\nFor children and adolescents, CCMD-3 provides specific criteria for diagnosing developmental and behavioral disorders, such as ADHD, conduct disorder, and social anxiety disorder. It also addresses specific school skill disorders, including reading, writing, and calculation disorders, as well as speech and language impairments. The classification system retains the concept of neurasthenia and categorizes neurosis into various subtypes, while also addressing personality disorders and adaptation disorders.\n\nOverall, CCMD-3 is a robust and culturally adapted diagnostic manual that reflects the unique clinical and cultural context of mental health in China, offering a structured approach to the classification and diagnosis of mental disorders across all age groups.", "EYSENCK:Eysenck等认为，个性古板、严肃、多愁善感、焦虑、悲观、保守、敏感、孤僻的人易患神经症。", "巴甫洛夫:", "WHO:The World Health Organization (WHO) is a global organization dedicated to addressing health-related issues worldwide. It provides comprehensive statistics and guidance on various health topics, including the burden of non-communicable diseases such as mental illnesses. In 2001, the WHO published a significant report focusing on mental health, aiming to raise awareness about the importance of mental well-being and the substantial burden posed by mental disorders. Additionally, the organization offers detailed global health statistics and classifications, which encompass data on the prevalence of neurosis and other mental health conditions. Through its efforts, the WHO plays a crucial role in advancing global health knowledge and promoting strategies to improve mental health outcomes.", "1982年12个地区精神疾病流行病学调查:A 1982 epidemiological survey in 12 regions of China that reported a neurosis prevalence rate of 2.2%", "1993年7地区调查:A 1993 survey in 7 regions of China that reported a neurosis prevalence rate of 1.5%"], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-v3"}}}